HAND, FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - SINGAPORE (03): EPIDEMIOLOGY
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 17 Jun 2015
Source: Channel News Asia [edited]
http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/hfmd-cases-50-higher-than/1920972.html


The number of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) cases as of mid-June 2015 has exceeded 14 000, nearly 50 per cent higher than during a similar period last year [2014]. However, doctors say this is not a cause for major concern, given that most cases are relatively mild strains of the virus. The figures saw an early rise from early April 2015, peaking at 1004 cases in the 1st week of May 2015 before easing off.

A Ministry of Health (MOH) spokesperson, noting that HFMD is a common childhood disease that is endemic to Singapore, said on Tue 16 Jun 2015 that "increases in cases can be expected from time to time." The spokesperson added: "The predominant circulating strains this year [2015] are coxsackieviruses type A, which typically cause mild disease. No severe cases or deaths due to HFMD have been reported in the past 3 years."

As of 13 Jun 2015, 14 237 HFMD cases were reported to MOH. In comparison, 9684 cases were reported between January and 7 Jun last year [2014]. Of this year's [2015] cases, 72 per cent were patients aged below 7.

"The key to controlling outbreaks of infectious diseases such as HFMD is the early detection and isolation of cases (children with HFMD should stay at home till they are well), and the maintenance of high levels of personal and environmental hygiene," the spokesperson said.

Meanwhile, general practitioners told the press they had seen slight increases in HFMD cases recently, compared with a year ago. Dr Sunil Joseph of Tayka Medical Family Clinic in Jurong said the cases he had attended to so far were "mild cases, where the strain of the virus is not too virulent."

While several parents expressed concern over the increase in HFMD cases, they told journalists they were confident their children's schools could handle the matter effectively. A parent who has a daughter in kindergarten said: "We are trusting the school to provide us with updates on suspected HFMD cases so we as parents can take precautions accordingly."

Several kindergartens and childcare centres noted isolated cases of HFMD on their premises. However, they added that they had protocols -- such as temperature and health checks -- in place, along with regular sanitation practices.

