[Hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) is a common infectious disease of infants and children. It is characterized by fever, painful sores in the mouth, and a rash with blisters on hands, feet and also buttocks. It is prevalent in many Asian countries. Outbreaks of HFMD occur every few years in different parts of the world, but in recent years, these have occurred more in Asia. Countries with recent large increases in the numbers of reported cases in Asia include: China, Japan, Hong Kong (China), Republic of Korea (South Korea), Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, Taiwan and Viet Nam. HFMD outbreaks have been frequent in Singapore and neighbouring countries and are probably indicative of common features of rearing of children.

Viruses from the group called enteroviruses cause HFMD. There are many different types in the group, including polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, echoviruses and other enteroviruses. HFMD is most commonly caused by coxsackievirus A16, which usually results in a mild, self-limiting disease with few complications. However, HFMD is also caused by other enteroviruses, including enterovirus 71 (EV71), which has been associated with serious complications and may be fatal.

It is difficult to make useful comparisons of epidemics affecting different societies. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Singapore can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3445720,150.]
